    "explanation_english": "This problem can be solved using the Principle of Inclusion-Exclusion for three sets. Let C be the set of members who don't eat Chiku, P be the set of members who don't eat Papaya, and G be the set of members who don't eat Guava.\nWe are given:\n*   |C| = 8\n*   |P| = 9\n*   |G| = 8\n*   |P ∩ G| = 6 (don't eat Papaya and Guava)\n*   |C ∩ G| = 4 (don't eat Chiku and Guava)\n*   |P ∩ C| = 4 (don't eat Papaya and Chiku)\n*   |C ∩ P ∩ G| = 3 (don't eat all three fruits)\n\nThe question asks for the 'total number of these family members,' which in this context, refers to the total number of unique individuals who exhibit at least one of the 'don't eat' characteristics. This is equivalent to finding the size of the union of these three sets: |C U P U G|.\n\nUsing the Principle of Inclusion-Exclusion:\n|C U P U G| = |C| + |P| + |G| - (|P ∩ G| + |C ∩ G| + |P ∩ C|) + |C ∩ P ∩ G|\n|C U P U G| = 8 + 9 + 8 - (6 + 4 + 4) + 3\n|C U P U G| = 25 - 14 + 3\n|C U P U G| = 11 + 3\n|C U P U G| = 14\n\nTherefore, there are 14 unique family members who don't eat at least one of the mentioned fruits.",
